passages.text: USA | Medical Supplies & Devices Is Philips Coming Back the US in CPAP? Definitely (Maybe) Eventually

Recently, there has been speculation that Philips (Hold, Dormois) may be growing closer to a return to the US CPAP market, which has implications for RMD (Taylor, Hold) and distributors like AHCO (Hold, Tanquilut). Despite a supplier's increased forecast, we think this is due to OUS demand, not a US return. Speaking with PHIA, competitors, distributors, and other contacts, we think an early-/mid- '26 return is unlikely, seeing '27+ as more reasonable.

On 8.14, Kimball Electronics (KE, NC) announced results, including a \(5\%\) increase in medical sales. Kimball is a contract manufacturer for Sleep and Respiratory Care and noted that its increase was driven by a step- up in sales by its largest medical customer (PHIA), expecting growth to continue.

On the call, KE said this increase was a 'welcome reprieve' after a long period of decline during the FDA recall. As a reminder, PHIA recalled certain ventilators, bi- level PAPs, and CPAPs in June '21, and a federal court entered a consent decree with Philips Respironics in April '24. KE noted it was selected as the sole supplier for PHIA's respiratory care and higher- level assemblies business, with most production occurring in Thailand. Previously, KE was doing printed circuit board assemblies but is now doing full and final assembly, noting PHIA previously had its own footprint in the US. KE will be doing this for all of PHIA's manufacturing now, with PHIA not doing 'any of it'. KE expects 'modest growth' in the medical business.

These statements led some to speculate a return to the US market by PHIA in CPAP was imminent, coming as soon as 1H26 or mid- '26. We believe this is not the case. Speaking with PHIA, the company noted this uptick was due to demand outside the US. PHIA stated that the timing of re- entry into the US remains uncertain and is subject to the consent decree.

Regarding PHIA's mfg transition to KE, we would expect the transfer to have many stages, requiring setup and re- validation of new equipment, which could take years. Contract mfgs like KE would also still be subject to the consent decree. At the same time, in our discussions with other industry players, there have been no signs from customers that PHIA is coming back (soon) or building a salesforce. At this stage, we do not expect PHIA to come back for at least another 1- 2 years. Other experts have noted it could take 5- 7 years, with PHIA referencing an average consent decree has a 5- year window, but an injunction could be lifted earlier; see our deep dive here.

For RMD, growth OUS has continued to be healthy, despite PHIA re- entering other non- US markets. That said, our checks historically and speaking with distributors point to a willingness of US DMEs or from upstart React Medical (private), e.g., Generally, distributors are looking for discounts, with React Selling at a \(\sim 15\%\) discount to RMD, per our recent discussions with them. In historical checks, distributors we have interviewed have told us they would want at least a \(10\%\) discount from PHIA to bring product back in (notes: 6.20.25, 6.19.25, 6.25.24, survey).

Net- net, we see PHIA's eventual re- entry as a competitive risk long term for RMD but see nothing imminent on the horizon. Ultimately, we think PHIA could regain at least \(10 - 15\%\) market share following re- entry based on expert checks, with some expecting it to claw back more over time. React also aspires to achieve \(\sim 25\%\) share of new starts in the next 12M. PHIA will host a CMD in Feb '26; we think investors will look to that event for additional updates on market re- entry from PHIA.

Our price target is derived by applying a discount to our peer group average ratio of 1.5x EBITDA growth to our 2025 estimate and assuming a mid- single- digit LT EBITDA growth outlook. Risks include acquisition integration and increases in GLP- 1 utilization decrease CPAP TAM.

Our Base Case PT of \(\) 290\$ is based on \(\sim 25x\) our FY27E EPS, implying multiple stability from here and a lower multiple vs. history. Downside risks include GLP1s, margin pressures from inflation, supply chain and pricing pressure, litigation, increased competition, and continued macro headwinds. Upside risks include M&A activity, improved supply chain, the main competitor continuing to be out of the market, a lack of GLP1 impact, and improvement in the macro environment.

Our price target is derived from the weighted avg of DCF and SOTP using peer multiples for each division. Risks to the upside include China recovering steeply, strong market share gains in Imaging, margin expanding at a fast pace and earlier- than- expected resumption of sales of Respironics devices. Conversely, prolonged China uncertainties, renewed quality issues and reduced Capex plans for hospitals in US/Europe could all dampen confidence.
